1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ {is harmless} Bd7 {this is more 
straight-forward than the more popular alternative Nbd7 as it resolves the problem of 
the light-squared bishopimmediately} 6. Qxc4 Bc6 7. Bg2 Nbd7 8. Nc3 {this is more 
critical, white fights for the e4-square immediately} Nb6 9. Qd3 Bb4 {black also 
fights for control of the e4-square} 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 h6 {it's useful to prevent 
Bg5, even though we saw that black has a good way to develop his pieces even if white 
plays it} 12. Ne5 {allows exchanges} Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qe7 {c5 is also quite good} 14. 
Ne4 Rad8 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 16. Qf3 Qxf3+ 17. Nxf3 Nc4 $11 {1/2-1/2 (30) 
Petrovs,V-Alekhine,A Buenos Aires 1939} *

