fights for control of the e4-square} 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 h6 {it's useful to prevent 
Bg5, even though we saw that black has a good way to develop his pieces even if white 
plays it} 12. Bd2 Qe7 13. a3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Rfd8 15. Be1 Rac8 $5 {this is interesting 
as it shows how the game develops in these structures. It also illustrates how black 
should fight for the white squares in the centre} 16. Bf1 Bd5 {threatening ...c5} 17. 
b4 Nbd7 18. Nh4 Ne4 19. Qc2 Nd6 20. f3 g5 $1 21. Ng2 f5 $1 {control of e4 is 
everything} 22. Bf2 Nf6 {with complicated play: 0-1 (57) Smyslov,V-Keres,P The 
Hague/Moscow 1948} *

