[Comment "on-the-way-to-the-queens-gambit-declined/course/4642, variation/153482"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bd7 {this became popular several years 
ago. Black wants to solve the problem with the Bc8 so white's next move is 
practically forced if he wants to fight for an advantage.} 6. Ne5 Bc6 7. Nxc6 Nxc6 8. 
O-O Qd7 9. e3 Rd8 $5 {this is the latest attempt. Previously black played long 
castle, but white had better chances for an attack even though the positions were 
usuallydouble-edged. The rook move aims for active play in the centre by ...e5.} 10. 
Nc3 Be7 11. Qe2 e5 12. Qxc4 exd4 13. Rd1 O-O 14. Bxc6 {otherwise white cannot 
recuperate the pawn on d4} Qxc6 15. Qxc6 bxc6 16. exd4 Rfe8 {with no problems for 
black as he has comfortable play against the isolated pawn on d4 as compensation for 
the doubled c-pawns} *

