[SourceTitle "02 The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "on-the-way-to-the-queens-gambit-declined/course/4642, variation/151555"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 {more likely than not this will transpose to the main 
line. There are only a couple of minor options when white can play differently and 
these are analysed here.} 4. e3 Nc6 5. Bb5 $6 {this is considered dubious after the 
famous game Kamsky-Gelfand from their Candidates match in 2007.} cxd4 6. exd4 Qa5+ $1 
7. Nc3 Bg4 8. O-O e6 {this is some sort of a reversed Ragozin where black has easy 
play on the queenside and white still needs to re-route the awkward Nc3. Black's play 
in the model game that follows is how black should treat these positions.} 9. h3 Bxf3 
10. Qxf3 Rc8 11. Rfd1 Be7 12. Bf1 O-O 13. Ne2 b5 {the typical minority attack} 14. c3 
b4 15. Qd3 Qb6 16. cxb4 Nxb4 17. Qb3 Ne4 {and black is the one pressing here: 0-1 
(58) Kamsky, G (2705) -Gelfand,B (2733) Elista 2007} *

[Event "On the way to the Queen's Gambit Declined"]
[Site "The London System"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The London System 3"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "02 The London System"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "on-the-way-to-the-queens-gambit-declined/course/4642, variation/151556"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 {more likely than not this will transpose to the main 
line. There are only a couple of minor options when white can play differently and 
these are analysed here.} 4. e3 Nc6 5. Be2 {is harmless as after the typical} cxd4 6. 
exd4 Bf5 7. c3 e6 {we have arrived at the 'tabiya' where white has prematurely 
developed his bishop on e2} 8. Nh4 Nh5 $1 {is a nice retort} 9. Bxh5 Qxh4 $11 *

