1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {this has become the more popular move order lately, but in our case 
it doesn't make a difference because even after 2 Nf3 Nf6 3 Bf4 we're headed towards 
the 'tabiya' that arises after black's 8th move. This is very convenient for black as 
he can concentrate on studying the tabiya - it will arise in the vast majority of 
times and the alternatives are few and give him good play.} Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. dxc5 Qa5+ 
{after Nc6 white has 5 Bb5 and things are not that simple. After the text move black 
makes sure to get the pawn on c5} 5. Nc3 a6 $1 {preventing Nb5 in case of ...Qc5} 6. 
Nf3 Qxc5 7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O e6 {and with ...Be7 and ...O-O black will finish 
development. The Nc3 hinders white's central play and this makes the position easier 
to play with black.} *

