1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 {this has become the more popular move order lately, but in our case 
it doesn't make a difference because even after 2 Nf3 Nf6 3 Bf4 we're headed towards 
the 'tabiya' that arises after black's 8th move. This is very convenient for black as 
he can concentrate on studying the tabiya - it will arise in the vast majority of 
times and the alternatives are few and give him good play.} Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. 
Nd2 cxd4 6. exd4 Bf5 7. Qb3 Qc8 8. Ngf3 e6 {this is the 'tabiya' that will most 
likely arise if you play against a dedicated 'Londoner'} 9. Nh4 {the only way to 
create something, otherwise black has very easy play} Bg4 {this is less frequent than 
Be4, which is the main move here, but it is safer} 10. Bd3 Be7 11. Nhf3 Bh5 12. O-O 
Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 {and black is fine after ...O-O and the exchange of the 
black-squared bishops. He can even try to be aggressive, as in the following game} 
14. Ne1 Nh5 15. Bg3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 Qc7 17. Nd3 O-O-O $1 18. Nf3 Rh6 {with attack: 0-1 
(23) Anikonov,D (2370) -Rublevsky,S (2692) Khanty-Mansiysk 2015} *

