1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {the Trompowsky isn't that effective when the knight is still on g8, 
but some Tromp die-hards like to play like this} h6 3. Bh4 c6 {black's plan is 
simple: he plays ...Qb6, develops the bishop on f5 and then plays ...e6 (or ...e5 in 
the lines when white delays Nf3) with easy play} 4. e3 {this allows black to push 
...e5 in view of the undefended Bh4} Qb6 5. Qc1 e5 6. Nf3 exd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. Bg3 Bf5 
9. Be2 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. c4 {the only active plan white has in this position} Ne4 
12. Nc3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Be6 $11 14. c5 Qc7 15. b4 Nd7 16. b5 Bf6 {black is very solid 
with no weaknesses and the pair of bishops} 17. Qd2 {1/2-1/2 (24) Douriet Duany,A 
(2302) -Colovic,A (2471) Balaguer 2008} Rfe8 {this is more ambitious than b6 as I 
played in the game, which led to simplifications anddraw} 18. Rab1 Nf8 {and the 
knight wants to go to e6 from where it will exert pressure on d4. The Be6 will go 
either to f5 or g4.} *

