1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 {the Trompowsky isn't that effective when the knight is still on g8, 
but some Tromp die-hards like to play like this} h6 3. Bh4 c6 {black's plan is 
simple: he plays ...Qb6, develops the bishop on f5 and then plays ...e6 (or ...e5 in 
the lines when white delays Nf3) with easy play} 4. Nf3 Qb6 5. b3 Bf5 6. e3 e6 7. Be2 
Be7 8. Bxe7 Nxe7 9. O-O O-O 10. c4 Nd7 11. Nc3 {this is a typical position that can 
arise in this line - black has a solid position and no weaknesses so he first puts 
the rooks in the centre and then aims to strike with ...c5 or ...e5 (if allowed) .} 
Rad8 12. h3 Rfe8 {and a further regrouping can be ...Qc7 with ...Nc8-d6, ...Bg6 and 
eventually ...e5 (if possible) .} *

