[Comment "on-the-way-to-the-queens-gambit-declined/course/4642, variation/151666"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {this is less good than the London System because it 
improves the position of the black knight - it's obvious it is more active on e4 than 
onf6} Ne4 4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 Qb6 6. Nc3 {after 6 Qc1 black has smooth development after 
...Nc6, ...Bf5, ...Rc8, ...e6 and ...Be7 or ...Bd6} Nxc3 7. bxc3 Qa5 8. Qd2 Nc6 9. c4 
{otherwise black will finish development and will have concrete play against the 
doubled pawns} dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 cxd4 12. exd4 f6 {blunting both the Nf3 
and Bh4} 13. Rhe1 Na5 14. Bd3 Kf7 15. Rab1 g6 {and black will finish development with 
...Bh6 and ...b6 and ...Bb7 when he will start his play against the c and d-pawns} *

