1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {this is less good than the London System because it 
improves the position of the black knight - it's obvious it is more active on e4 than 
onf6} Ne4 4. Bf4 c5 5. c3 $6 cxd4 6. cxd4 Nc6 7. Nc3 {having wasted a tempo on 
Bg5-f4, now white is a tempo down compared to the line in the Slav (1 d4 d5 2 c4 c6 3 
cd cd 4 Nc3 Nf6 5 Nf3 Nc6 5 Bf4 Ne4)} Nxc3 8. bxc3 g6 {the Bg7 will be very useful to 
protect the king and keep an eye on the centre in case white decides to push e4 or 
c4} 9. e3 Bg7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Na5 {and black has the straightforward plan to play 
against the backward c3-pawn} *

