1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {Jobava's favourite, but not particularly threatening 
after black's next move} a6 $1 {cutting out ideas based on Nb5 and by securing b5 
black's natural development with ...c5 follow smoothly. In this line it's safer to 
keep the bishop on c8 as putting it on f5 invites some aggressive play by white after 
f3 and g4} 4. e3 e6 5. Nf3 c5 6. a3 b5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 {Carlsen develops the 
knight to d7 so as not to block the Bb7, which controls e4} 9. Re1 Be7 10. Ne5 O-O 
11. Nxd7 Nxd7 12. Qh5 f5 13. h3 Rc8 14. Bh2 {0-1 (55) Jobava,B (2702) -Carlsen,M 
(2840) Doha QAT 2016} Bf6 $1 {this is stronger than Carlsen's Qb6, which is also good 
for black} 15. Bf1 Qb6 {and d4 is under severe attack} *

