1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov Attack} c6 {this is actually a small 
provocation, as black can also start with 3.. .Nbd7 and then most probably transpose 
to the lines we analyse. The point of the provocation is to nudge white to take on 
f6, which some Veresov players like to do, but then black has excellent play} 4. Bxf6 
$6 {is what black is hoping for} exf6 {now black's plan is simple: he will play ... 
f5, ...Bd6, ...O-O, ...Nd7-f6-e4 and then probably ...Re8, ...g6 and ...h5 to expand 
on the kingside. This can all be played automatically and white's problem is that he 
doesn't have the usual plan in these positions, which is to play c4, as in the 
Trompowsky, because his knight is already on c3! This is the whole point of black's 
provocation.} 5. e3 f5 6. Bd3 Bd6 7. Qf3 g6 8. h4 h5 9. Nge2 Nd7 {and the knight will 
happily land on e4 in 2 moves} *

