1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 {The Veresov Attack} c6 {this is actually a small 
provocation, as black can also start with 3.. .Nbd7 and then most probably transpose 
to the lines we analyse. The point of the provocation is to nudge white to take on 
f6, which some Veresov players like to do, but then black has excellent play} 4. f3 
$6 {let's take this as the main line, as it's another typical Vereson idea, to build 
a centre by f3 and e4, even though it is not very good here.} Nbd7 5. e4 dxe4 6. fxe4 
e5 $1 7. dxe5 Qa5 8. exf6 {this wins a pawn for white but leaves him with horribly 
weak dark squares. The alternatives aren't better either.} Qxg5 9. fxg7 Bxg7 {black 
has marvellous compensation here.} 10. Qd2 Qxd2+ {following Mikhail Tal. I played Qa5 
here and I also won, but I think Tal's move is objectively better} 11. Kxd2 Nc5 12. 
Bd3 Be6 13. Nf3 O-O-O {the game is a good illustration of black's long-term 
compensation for the pawn - white is suffering because of his weak dark squares.} 14. 
Ke2 b5 15. a3 a5 16. h3 Rhe8 17. Rhd1 f5 $1 {opening up the position} 18. e5 {white 
cannot afford to open the position} Nd7 19. Re1 Bxe5 20. Kf2 {unfortunately white 
cannot kill the strong bishop} Bf6 {and now the material is equal while black's 
initiative is still here - Tal won in 8 more moves.} 21. Re3 Nc5 22. Rae1 Kd7 23. 
Nxb5 f4 24. Re5 Nxd3+ 25. cxd3 cxb5 26. Rxb5 Rb8 27. Ne5+ Kd6 28. Rxa5 Bh4+ {0-1 (28) 
Alburt,L (2450) -Tal,M (2625) Baku 1972} *

