1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c4 {this can transpose to several openings: Caro-Kann 
(the Panov Attack), Semi-Tarrasch, Grunfeld and QGA, all depending on how black 
continues.} cxd4 5. exd4 g6 {this development is the best here - the Bg7 will be 
excellent against white's isolated pawn} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bc4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 
Qc7 10. Qb3 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 12. Be2 Be6 13. Qa3 Rac8 14. Rb1 Rfd8 15. Be3 Na5 {black 
is already better, having placed his pieces on the perfect squares. Anand's play in 
this game is exemplary.} 16. Rfc1 Nc4 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Qxa7 Bd5 {threatening 
...Ra8-a2} 19. Qb6 Bxa2 20. Qxc7 Rxc7 21. Rb6 Rdc8 22. Bd2 Bd5 23. Ne5 e6 24. f3 Ra8 
25. Nd3 Ra2 26. Rb2 Ra3 27. Nc5 e5 $1 {and black went on to win in: 0-1 (36) Hebden,M 
(2527) -Anand,V (2792) London 2014} *

