1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. b3 {the Zukertort System was used by Carlsen in his 
match against Karjakin, but it isn't very scary} Nc6 {Karjakin played e6 and later 
developed the Nb8 to d7. By developing the knight to c6 and the bishop to g4 black 
prevents any possible attacks based on Ne5, f4 etc. (which is the main idea for white 
in the Zukertort) .} 5. Bb2 Bg4 6. Be2 e6 {white is playing the Tartakower line in 
the QGD, as if he's black} 7. O-O Bd6 8. Nbd2 O-O {black finished development and his 
subsequent plan is to play ...Qe7 or ...Qc7 and put the rooks on c8 andd8} 9. Ne5 $6 
{this is dubious} Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Qc7 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. h3 cxd4 13. exd4 a5 $15 {and 
black is already better - the Bb2 is very passive and black can play both on the 
queenside by ...a4 and in the centre by ...c5 and/or ...Ne4 (if allowed) .} *

